objects.name: Rancor Taurus
objects.description:
RANCOR Taurus, also known as Rancor, is a threat actor behind two campaigns of attacks in South East Asia researched by Unit42 in mid-2018.

The RANCOR Taurus attackers are notable for repeated use of plugin based malware architectures where the malware downloads functionality in the form of plugins or modules. Malware families observed in use in this campaign include: PlainTee and DDKong

The attackers may also be behind a previous campaign targeting Cambodia using KHRAT.

objects.name: June 2018 Cambodia
objects.description:
Rancor Taurus targeted Cambodia sending HTML Application files to target most likely as an email attachment. When Opened and executed, the key components of the HTA file downloads and executes further malware from a remote URL and loads a decoy image hosted externally

The threat group also used the DLL loader as delivery.  The loader downloads the malware and configures it for persistent execution. It also downloads and opens a decoy PDF document hosted on a legitimate but compromised website. The decoy documents seen in these cases were related to Cambodian news articles.

objects.name: December 2018 Cambodia
objects.description: Between early December 2018 and the end of January 2019, Rancor Taurus conducted at least two rounds of attacks to one Cambodia goverment organization.While researching these attacks, Unit 42 discovered an undocumented, custom malware family  named Dudell. In addition, we discovered the group using Derusbi, which is a malware family believed to be unique to a small subset of Chinese cyber espionage groups.

objects.name: June 2018 Singapore
objects.description: Unit 42 believes the attackers behind these attacks are conducting their campaigns for espionage purposes. We identified decoy files that indicate these attacks began with spear-phishing messages but have not observed the actual messages. These decoys contain details from public news articles focused primarily on political news and events. Based on this, we believe the Rancor Taurus attackers were targeting political entities.  Additionally, these decoy documents are hosted on legitimate websites including a government website belonging to the Cambodia Government and in at least once case, Facebook.

objects.name: PLAINTEE
objects.description:
PlainTee is a plugin-based malware family that uses a custom UDP protocol to download plugins.
Of the plugins observed, these also use the same custom UDP protocol for communications, making this a noteworthy malware family.
Plugins observed so far include:
* Plugins to aid in file system manipulations (CRUD operations)
* Plugins to allow process manipulation (delete, start, kill)

The malware is fairly rare and is used solely in targeted attacks.

objects.name: DUDELL
objects.description: DUDELL is a dropper malware family that has been attributed to the Rancor Taurus threat actor group. The malware comes in a variety of forms. Variants in 2018 made use of malicious macros within Word documents, while variants in 2019 make use of Office-based exploits to ultimately deliver a side-loaded malicious DLL that will carry out the necessary commands. The malware attempts to download a remote payload via either the 'certutil' or 'msiexec' build-in Windows utilities. The remote payload is dropped within a subdirectory in the victim's %windir%\system32\spool\drivers\color\ path. Persistence is performed via scheduled tasks on the victim machine.

objects.name: KHRAT
objects.description: KHRAT is a small backdoor that has three exports (functions), namely, K1, K2, and K3. K1 checks if the current user is an administrator. If not, it uninstalls itself by calling the K2 function. K3 then elevates the malware’s privilege, by giving itself SE_DEBUG_PRIVILEGE privileges via a RtlAdjustPrivileges call, and proceeds to communicate to its command and control (C2) server. The malware initially registers itself to the C2 server by sending the infected machine’s username, system language, and local IP address. All communication to and from the C2 server are encrypted in byte-wise XOR.
